diagnose_result._raw:
{
  "diagnosis": "Actinic keratosis",
  "confidence": "Medium",
  "reasoning": {
    "query_summary": "Small (approx 3–4 mm) irregular, asymmetrical macule on sun‑damaged facial skin. Central area is pale/skin‑colored to light pink and smoother; peripheral rim contains multiple discrete to confluent light-to-dark brown clods/dots and a few tiny black peppering specks. Surrounding background shows diffuse erythema and fine linear/branching telangiectatic vessels that extend into adjacent skin. No obvious pigment network, globules with typical melanocytic symmetry, or clear milia-like cysts are seen. Surface scale/keratin is not clearly resolved.",
    "synthesis": "I confirm the Triage Agent family assignment of Keratinocytic. The image shows classic features that support a keratinocytic, sun‑damage–associated lesion: (1) small lesion on chronically photodamaged facial skin; (2) central pale/atrophic zone rather than a uniform pigmented lesion; (3) irregular peripheral brown clods and superficial punctate dark specks consistent with focal pigmented keratinocyte change or scale adherent to the surface; and (4) prominent fine linear/branching vessels that traverse lesion and background — a common finding in actinic keratoses on the face. These concrete dermoscopic findings align with the lab report items: peripheral brown clods/dots, central hypopigmented/atrophic zone, punctate peppering, telangiectasia, and sun‑damaged background (agreement).

Contradictions / uncertainties relative to the lab report: the lab noted possible superficial keratin/crust but marked it indeterminate; on the image I cannot confidently confirm surface scale or keratin (so I downgrade that feature to indeterminate). The lab described irregular asymmetry which matches the image; there are no strong features of basal cell carcinoma (no large arborizing vessels, no translucent pearly quality) and no convincing melanocytic structures (no pigment network, no streaks/pseudopods) — so I do not favor melanoma or melanocytic nevus.

Rationale for selecting Actinic keratosis specifically (rather than pigmented benign keratosis or BCC): actinic keratosis on facial photodamaged skin commonly appears as a small erythematous-to‑pink macule with focal superficial pigmentation and fine telangiectasia; the central atrophic/pale zone with peripheral brown speckling fits pigmented AK morphology. Pigmented seborrheic keratosis would more often show moth‑eaten borders, milia‑like cysts/comedo‑like openings or thicker stuck‑on scale — none of which are clearly visible. Basal cell carcinoma often has larger arborizing vessels and a translucent/pearly quality, which are not seen here. Because the surface keratin finding is indeterminate and some features (brown clods, tiny dots) could overlap with other keratinocytic entities, I assign a Medium confidence rather than High. If clinical concern persists, correlation with palpation for scale/roughness or biopsy/excision is recommended."
}}

